    <item>
      <title>Fire after fire</title>
      <link>https://www.dhakatribune.com/opinion/editorial/409820/fire-after-fire</link>
      <description>It is infuriating how, one after the other, we have fires reducing factories to ashes.

While it is a relief that there were no reported casualties, the blaze at Kadamtali’s foam factory is only the latest in a long line of tragedies that expose the same disregard for safety, the same negligence, and the same cycle of promises that never translate into change.

Every time a fire breaks out, probes are announced. Committees are formed, reports are written, and recommendations are made. Yet year after year, the same hazards persist - blocked exits, faulty wiring, flammable materials stored without precaution, and workers left without training or protection.

The investigations rarely lead to structural reforms and instead, they fade into bureaucratic silence, while the next fire waits to happen.

This disregard has become systemic and it is our nation and our people that continue to suffer as a result.

Factory owners cut corners, regulators look the other way, and accountability is absent. The repetition of these fires cannot be dismissed as accidental. They are the predictable outcome of a system that refuses to learn.

Bangladesh cannot afford this complacency and fire safety must be treated with the seriousness it has long demanded, not a seasonal headline. That means enforcing building codes, holding owners accountable, and ensuring that safety inspections are legitimate and not just another checkmark.

Most of all, it means that probes must lead to actions that are visible, measurable, and lasting.

The Kadamtali fire is part of a pattern and breaking that pattern requires a concerted effort. It requires courage from policy-makers, responsibility from owners, and vigilance from regulators.

Empty probes will not save lives nor stop the fires. We must decide whether we will continue to burn in cycles of negligence or finally commit to a system where safety is non‑negotiable.</description>
